1240
01:28:34,361 --> 01:28:42,708
A chorus of people from across Medford have reached out to their elected officials in the last week and two to demand anti-racist action from our city.

1241
01:28:43,549 --> 01:28:49,074
I've only been a city councilor for a few months, but this is by far the most contact I've received from Medford residents.

1242
01:28:49,995 --> 01:28:53,778
The murders of George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, Ahmaud Arbery,

1243
01:28:54,194 --> 01:29:05,718
and thousands of other black Americans at the hands of police are horrific and yet all too common examples of the ongoing violence of white supremacy and structural racism in our country and right here in our community.

1244
01:29:06,718 --> 01:29:14,781
Medford residents, especially young black residents, are sharing stories online about the racism and hate that they've experienced in our schools and on our streets.

1245
01:29:15,761 --> 01:29:22,944
While some people were shocked by these horrific accounts, people commit racist acts or make racist remarks every single day in Medford.

1246
01:29:23,668 --> 01:29:31,393
The many people who spoke at the powerful Black Lives Matter vigil at Hormel Stadium last week confirmed those stories of racism in our community and shared more of their own.

1247
01:29:32,734 --> 01:29:34,255
I attended the Medford public schools.

1248
01:29:34,936 --> 01:29:38,438
I remember the racist and hateful remarks that I would hear on a near daily basis.

1249
01:29:39,339 --> 01:29:44,002
It doesn't surprise me to know that this racism was even worse than I knew or that I could see as a white student.

1250
01:29:44,923 --> 01:29:46,284
None of us did enough to stop it.

1251
01:29:46,924 --> 01:29:48,865
And sometimes we didn't do anything at all.

1252
01:29:49,966 --> 01:29:51,247
Racism is a Medford problem.

1253
01:29:52,578 --> 01:29:57,661
Medford has a deep history, and some of that is a deep history of racism, and we don't talk about it.

1254
01:29:58,262 --> 01:30:09,709
Medford also has a deep history of anti-racist organizing, of abolitionists, and of black-led movements for racial equity and justice for all, which we almost never talk about as a community.

1255
01:30:10,610 --> 01:30:18,435
I want to particularly note the story of Shirley Kuntz, who in the late 1960s fought to desegregate the Hervey School, where I attended elementary school.

1256
01:30:19,430 --> 01:30:28,832
Medford Historical Society hosts on their website a history of the many African American Medford residents who have fought racial injustices and advocated for everyone in our community.

1257
01:30:29,872 --> 01:30:36,873
Medford residents of color have repeatedly stood up and demanded change and a real commitment to fight racism in Medford, even in the recent past.

1258
01:30:37,674 --> 01:30:43,555
But as I've heard too often this week from people who fought for that change, they said, quote, still nothing has changed.

1259
01:30:44,695 --> 01:30:45,055
No more.

1260
01:30:46,126 --> 01:30:50,309
First, we have to declare systemic racism as a public health emergency here in Medford.

1261
01:30:51,110 --> 01:30:57,795
One of the deepest impacts of racism are the racial health disparities that lead to poor medical treatment, illness, and death for people of color.

1262
01:30:58,536 --> 01:31:10,885
This was the subject of my undergraduate thesis at UMass Amherst, and we know that even after you control for income or wealth or any other factor, Black people and people of color have worse health outcomes just because of their race.

1263
01:31:11,646 --> 01:31:15,669
The increased illness and early death of our neighbors and friends is an emergency.

1264
01:31:17,035 --> 01:31:27,420
This declaration is one of the municipal actions requested as part of the 10-point agenda from the Massachusetts Black and Latino Legislative Caucus, and they were joined with many elected officials of color from across the state.

1265
01:31:28,420 --> 01:31:41,126
